They package an extension that LibreOffice incorporates as the default tool for European Portuguese:> http://extensions.libreoffice.org/extension-center/corretor-ortografico-para-portugues-de-portugal-1> It as passed several week and they have not yet replied to any of my e-mails, but it is still summer season, so I believe we should wait a couple more weeks. I know the work is good and significantly better than the previous version, but I would prefer to have them review, in order to avoid offending anyone.>> The files I had packaged are:>     - 'th_pt_PT_v2.dat'        - Thesaurus main data file. Contains word relations. Made by me.>     - 'th_pt_PT_v2.idx'        - Thesaurus index file. I can rename it if required.> These files should go to /libreoffice/dictionaries/tree/pt_PT/>>     - 'standard-fontes cont├®m palavras em pt_BR.dic' This file was only included to assist dictionary maintainers.>> Sorry for another wall of text.> Have a nice weekend.>> Tiago Santos-------------------------------------------

Patch Set 5:Looks great, but there were some bugs and tweaks that are needed.Default should be the first entry in the submenu menu.If set to notebookbar, restarting LO wont show notebookbar and changing it to another mode and then back to notebookbar wont make it appear.If notebookbar is enabled, .uno:AvailableToolbars should be disabled.If notebookbar isnt enabled, .uno:Notebookbar should be disabled.For default mode, if the sidebar is opened/closed/only showing the 'show' arrow button, it should be opened only showing the tab bars (what it looks like when you open writer with a cleared profile).For single toolbar mode, the sidebar should be enabled but collapsed only showing the 'show' arrow button, the toolbar icons need to be changed to small if they are set to automatic and the icon style should be changed to sifr if set to automatic. this means that before the activation of single toolbar mode, the icon size and style needs to be preserved in the user profile for non-single toolbar mode, as well as saving it for when exiting single toolbar mode so it can be restored when returning to single toolbar mode. In this mode, all contextual toolbar should be disabled (https://bugs.documentfoundation.org/show_bug.cgi?id=92218#c13).For sidebar mode, the sidbear should be fully opened whatever state it is in and set to the properties tab.For notebookbar mode, the sidebar should be collapsed to show the 'show' arrrow button, similar to single toolbar mode.

Patch Set 2:> Note that some sub-menus are implemented as separate popup menu > controllers, and as such populated only upon menu activation. So if > you really need the full menu structure without executing the vcl > menu, you should at least do a fake call to the vcl menu activation > callback. (The other alternative would be to change > ResourceMenuController to create the MenuBarManager instance > earlier for this case, and then change also MenuBarManager::FillMenuManager > to create the controllers).I opted for the first one: doing a fake call, and that seemed to have done the trick. >  > But be aware that some popup menu controllers don't use standart > dispatch command for their items, as they implement them > internally. Patch Set 1:To elaborate on how to amend a patch: The trick here is preserving the same Change-Id of the commit message, so that Gerrit recognizes it should be on the same thread. Locally, you do a new commit, then you do `git rebase -i HEAD~2' to squash that with the previous commit. Then you push and Gerrit will detect your updated squashed commit as a new version (or ÔÇ£patch setÔÇØ) without creating a new thread. Hope this helps!

Patch Set 1:> To elaborate on how to amend a patch: The trick here is preserving > the same Change-Id of the commit message, so that Gerrit recognizes > it should be on the same thread. Locally, you do a new commit, then > you do `git rebase -i HEAD~2' to squash that with the previous > commit.Git commit --amend is a much easier way to do that.iow checkout your gerrit patchdo the modificationscommit them using --amendgit push origin HEAD:refs/for/master Then you push and Gerrit will detect your updated squashed > commit as a new version (or ÔÇ£patch setÔÇØ) without creating a new > thread. Hope this helps!

Good to know. The reason I wrote this script is because I have another patch that improves pch generation (a rewrite of update_pch in python that updates every single pch in the codebase in a few seconds). It was obvious to me that to improve the pch generation to make builds faster I had to deal with the problem of conflicting headers (that are excluded from pch) and required headers (that will break the build if left out). This script solves the latter problem, so now what is included in pch headers is purely to accelerate builds, not to prevent the build from breaking.Will submit the update_pch script and updated pch files sometime soon, as time permits.

Patch Set 8: Code-Review-1The import part looks good, and functions very well.  Great job on doing your analysis and coming up with a very well thought-out solution.Now, the only remaining issue is the saving.  Right now, when you open a csv.gz file, edits it, and hits Ctrl-S, it saves it back to the file uncompressed, while the extension is intact.  This is not ideal.I can think of 2 ways to resolve this.  The first way is to support saving it back gz compressed, by somehow storing the information that this file has been uncompressed and using that information and trigger gz compression on saving.  In this scenario, you need to be careful not to compress on save when the user decides to save the file with a different name.  There would be other corner cases you'd have to handle when going this route. Personally I don't like this solution.The 2nd way is to load the file read only when the file is automatically uncompressed during file detection.  This way, when the user wants to edit it and re-save it, she won't be able to overwrite the original file.  I personally like this solution.Here is the gotcha, though.  Forcing a read-only load is as easy as setting the read only flag to true with the media descriptor, which will prompt you that the document has been opened read only, and to edit it, the user will need to click "Edit document" to create a new document instance.  When you do that, Calc will still load the compressed stream into the 2nd document instance, not the uncompressed version.  This needs to be addressed.I hope this will not be too much trouble to solve.  Good luck!

Patch Set 8:Great analysis!  I personally think that (assuming that it works) your approach 3) is the best approach under the circumstance.  Could you make the change for that and update your patch?  I'd like to give that a spin.One very minor thing I would change is to switch from replaceFirst() to copy() to get a substring of the original URL in order to remove the .gz extension.  Using replaceFirst is fine, but I personally find using the copy() method more "natural" for that sort of use given that you already have the position of the ".gz" string. Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1The patch looks completely reasonable from the POV of the current state of the code. However, code archaeology suggests that merge commit 67d2af6fac2d9bad52a6b1f6e0cbd1229eb88a42 erroneously removed the call to "ImplUpdate" in MoveItem, since that line is present in BOTH parents of that merge. The "if ( nNewPos < nPos )" seems to be done for the sake of the ImplUpdate, to set the argument it will be called with. It looks reasonable, since the call is made with the default value of bDirect==false, then ImplUpdate updates *all* columns after its first argument (its argument inclusive). So it is essentially called with ::std::min(nPos, nNewPos).So it seems to me that we should rather fix the error in bd24a310be1459510b760b812838cb87923853c5 of using "nPos" instead of "nNewPos" in the second call of ::std::advance (the one before insert), but leave the "if ( nNewPos < nPos )" and reinsert the "ImplUpdate(nPos, ...)".Kendy, I know it is far away, but would you agree with my analysis of your merge commit?Julien, could you try out my suggestion above and test its effects, if the behaviour is good, the bug is still fixed, no other obvious bug is introduced, etc? Thanks in advance.

Patch Set 1:Thank you very much for your feedback and your hints!I have thought about how to best implement this and would appreciate your feedback on my ideas.The possibilities I am currently thinking about are as follows:1) Add two new functions (e.g. "jfw_plugin_getJavaInfoFromJavaHome", "jfw_plugin_getJavaInfosFromPath") to vendorplugin.hxx and sunjavaplugin.cxx to obtain information about Java installations referred to by JAVA_HOME and PATH environment variables (similar to jfw_plugin_getAllJavaInfos). The two functions use the functions in util.cxx to get the information.jfw_findAndSelectJRE uses the two new functions to check for such Java installations and uses them if there are any, otherwise uses the algorithm that is currently used.This would avoid duplicate code in jfw_findAndSelectJRE and getAllJREInfos.2) Add additional (out) parameters to getAllJREInfos and jfw_plugin_getAllJavaInfos that hold the JavaInfos that have been found using JAVA_HOME or PATH.possible new signature:javaPluginError jfw_plugin_getAllJavaInfos(    rtl_uString *sVendor,    rtl_uString *sMinVersion,    rtl_uString *sMaxVersion,    rtl_uString * * arExcludeList,    sal_Int32  nSizeExcludeList,    JavaInfo*** parJavaInfo,    sal_Int32 *nSizeJavaInfo,    JavaInfo** parJavaInfoFromJavaHome,    JavaInfo*** parJavaInfosFromPath,    sal_Int32 *nSizeJavaInfosFromPath);If JAVA_HOME points to a suitable Java installation, parJavaInfoFromJavaHome points to it.If suitable Java installations are on the PATH, parJavaInfosFromPath holds the respective JavaInfos and nSizeJavaInfosFromPath is the number of JavaInfos found on the PATH.The additional parameters would be unused for "normal" calls to the method and only be used in jfw_findAndSelectJRE (which is possibly no good design?).3) Add an additional field to the _JavaInfo struct that tells how the Java installation has been found. I currently don't have a reasonable idea how to actually implement that field - which should be able to tell e.g. that the Java installation is referred to by JAVA_HOME, and/or is the 1st Java on the PATH, the 2nd Java on the PATH,..., or has been found in a different way.As far as I understand, the struct is defined in include/jvmfwk/framework.h and the new field would thus also be visible from outside the "jvmfwk" module.I personally consider solution 1) to be the best of those three, but would appreciate your feedback. Of course, a totally different solution is welcome, too.

Patch Set 12:ok so 2 things.1/ this patch start to suffer from feature creep.you know have 3 independents changes crammed into it.Let's keep these independent things in independents patches.(the JDK thing is orthogonal to the Python thing, which is orthogonal to the SDK thing)2/ I'm a bit confused by the rapid fire upload of new version.The idea of gerrit is to upload a version when you think it is ready for review... but here you got 7 version in rapid sequence without any review interaction.. and same after version 7...  Is the patch ready for review ? or should I wait for another hour for version n+1 ?iow:In a single patch: do one thing. Upload to gerrit when you think it is ready for review, ie ready, you think, to be merged.Review takes time too.. and every time you upload a new version it essentially invalidate the review done on the previous versionI'm encouraged by your patch.. there are good stuff in there.I'm just trying to adjust the process to make processing these patches easier for all involved :-)

As described in: http://social.msdn.microsoft.com/Forums/en-US/os_openXML-ecma/thread/1febafab-67d7-4a26-ac51-fec69a39c2fe/The cnfStyle doesn't have a function and should not be used to determine the table style, instead the tblLook property has to be used.I fixed this, I added a bugdoc that contains a table without cnfStyle Properties, this file looks bad in LO, but good in Word.As a side effect, now also the table corner styles are imported properly.Best regards,Sven

Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't submit thisHmm, I am not sure that I like this change. It does not create the formatting entry without any explanation. You were able to edit the unused formatting and add the range later in the past.For example, imagine that you define some formatting, forget to define the range, and press the "Add" button. You will not know why the entry was not created. You will need to select everything again and again until you find why it does not work :-)IMHO, the best solution would be to preffil the range with the current selected cell(s). For example, the DataPilot or Chart is created from the current selection by default as well.Hmm, the prefil would be annoying if you lose some older formatting  in the selected cells. In this case, I would prefer to leave the behavior as is and fix it with the error dialog for 4.1. IMHO, the behavior is more annoying with the patch than without it.BTW: I really like the conditional formatting. It is very cool and useful feature. Thanks a lot for the hard work in this area.

Patch Set 6:Oliver, I forgot to mention that, while this fix makes "Further comments on page <pagefield + n>." *possible*, it would require the user to go into that particular page number field and set the offset. That matches Microsoft Word's offset behavior. Offset is never globally applied across fields. It is applied manually to individual fields. A footer is just the most common instance (at which point, the one instance of the page number is offset on all footers because of the footer's functionality, not the page number's functionality).Whether we eventually abandon this or not (see immediately prior comment), I'll address your inline comment. Good catch!

Patch Set 2:Apologies for my late response on this issue. The following is my rationale for reverting strdup back into PL_strdup:--https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Mozilla/Projects/NSPR/About_NSPR"Memory managementNSPR provides API to perform the basic malloc, calloc, realloc and free functions. Depending on the platform, the functions may be implemented almost entirely in the NSPR runtime or simply shims that call immediately into the host operating system's offerings."-> thus replacing PL_strdup with strdup may cause different results on different platforms--https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Mozilla/Projects/NSPR/Reference/PL_strdup"Returns a pointer to a new memory node in the NSPR heap containing a copy of a specified string.Syntax#include <plstr.h>char *PL_strdup(const char *s);NotesThe memory allocated by PL_strdup should be freed with PL_strfree."--http://linux.die.net/man/3/strdup"DescriptionThe strdup() function returns a pointer to a new string which is a duplicate of the string s. Memory for the new string is obtained with malloc(3), and can be freed with free(3)."-> there is no guarantee that memory on the heap used by strdup (i.e. the heap used by malloc) can be freed using PL_strfree.--Due to these concerns, I would like to request for this change be reopened and re-evaluated. Thank you for your patience on this issue.

Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1OK - I've read the patch more carefully now...The comment "/// XStatusListener" is totally misleading.  Normally it means that the method implements XStatusListener UNO service, which scared me a lot, one has to be very careful introducing this :-) Having read it more carefully, it is not the case here luckily.Generally, please do not mix style changes with functional changes in the patches like this, then it looks like a much more complex change than it really is :-)  Of course it is OK to change the style of the actual lines you are touching, but when you do that for lines around too, it just makes the patch less readable.Also it is good to add comments to the places you are fixing / implementing - at least one line summary of purpose of a class is much appreciated.So I'd suggest the following: Split to more patches, where1) 1st patch turns ButtonStatusListener into VclStatusListener template liketemplate <class T> VclStatusListenerthat gets the widget as the template parameter, and calls its statusChanged() method.  In the toolbar code, the instantiation would look like mpStatusListener  = new WindowStatusListener<ToolBox>(this, ".uno:ImageOrientation");2) 2nd that actually implements the functionality for the toolbar.3) [optionally] some style clenaup arnoud, but better to avoid doing much of that.Also - is this all that was necessary to be done to fix the problem in the sidebar, or is an additional patch anticipated?Thank you for your work on this! :-) - and sorry about my initial reaction, the stylistic changes + the wrong comment triggered a warning light in my mind ;-)

Patch Set 1:> codify in UR that on non-Windows wchar_t is 32-bit and represents UTF-32 code unitsWell, that's an implementation "bug". When LibreOffice is ported to a platform where it is not the case, the implementation can be updated for this platform. Or we could implement this function in a more portable way, for example using iconv (but polishing the code to fix the memory leak and all that):static iconv_t cnv = iconv_open("UTF-16", "WCHAR_T");sal_Unicode *buf=calloc(len, 2*sizeof(sal_Unicode))size_t cnvlen =  sizeof(2*sal_Unicode*len)const size_t cps = iconv(cnv, &str, &len, &buf, &cnvlen)rtl_uStringbuffer_insert( &pData, &nCapacity, getLength(), buf, cps );I actually think implementing this feature in a robust way it would be a service to C++ extensions (even if it does not get used much within LibreOffice).As far as the needs of connectivity/odbc are concerned, I'm happy with the solution suggested by email.

Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1(1 comment)Hi Yogesh, thanks for looking into this.I was worried about the change to wrtw8sty.cxx so I had a bit of a look at the bug myself to understand it better.  I found two different issues which contribute:- the import from docx appears to have a bug which is at play here: when I open the docx in LibreOffice I see that the first page footer has wrong spacing. This affects the export code which tries to join chained page styles into a single word section if they match.  The import bug means that they do not match, so it will try to export this as two different word sections.- however some code recently added to ww8/ww8atr.cxx in a31fbb53dba7 prevents the output of a new section at the page break in this case, as the paragraph on the first page is empty             if( isTextNodeEmpty )                bNewPageDesc = false;So I think these are the two issues that need to be addressed, rather than the change proposed in this item.  Fixing either one of them will solve the reported issue for this document, but it would be great to fix both.

Patch Set 1:You are very brave for stepping into this can of worms :-)In lcl_ConvertTimeZone() in sax/source/tools/converter.cxx, you are attempting to convert times between timezones.I don't think this can be done safely without access to a DST (Daylight Savings Time) database.You need to know what DST offset was in operation at that specific source date, in order to be able to convert it to a UTC time, and then you need to know the DST offset for the destination date in order to correctly switch to it.See here for a good discussion:http://stackoverflow.com/questions/2532729/daylight-saving-time-and-timezone-best-practicesThe specific recommendation from that stackoverflow article that we should probably follow is that,if we are going to store a TZ offset with our Date/Time objects, we should also be storing a DST offset.Also, if we're going to create new commonly used types/structs, perhaps we can use shorter names, like DateTimeTZ?

Patch Set 1:Hi Tor,The remove-and-rebuild test is indeed the criteria that I'm using. There's too many files to check by hand so a automated or at least semi-automated approach is necessary.Anyway, thanks for the comments! I hadn't thought about indirect inclusion. How about this refined approach:For each .cxx file,1) Use the brute-force approach to find candidate headers for removal, and use "g++ -H" to dump out a full list of all included headers 2) If a candidate header shows up *once* in the list from g++ -H, it's definitely unnecessary and we remove it. If it shows up more than once (via indirect inclusion), then we leave it alone for now.This should give a smaller list of includes to remove, or in the case of no indirect inclusions, the same list.Are there any other pitfalls that are worth looking out for? Cheers,Michael

Patch Set 2: Do not submitThanks for tackling this issue ! I have a few comments however:It seems to me that using isalpha / isprint on string characters like this is a particularly horrible way to achieve this :-)To copy/paste a similar chunk of text twice like that is rather poor style - in programming for maintainability the aim is always to minimise the number of new lines we add: to maximise the sharing of lines of code etc.As such - I'd really strongly prefer as much of the if (rtl) { } cases to be shared with the non-rtl cases - can we not setup variables that alter the order of iteration / layout placement / rendering in advance and then use them in a shared block later ?When we do:+            // this code are for reverse the number of sildes in TitleThe title we have there seems to come from:void PresenterPaneBase::PaintBorder (const awt::Rectangle& rUpdateBox)...            mxBorderPainter->paintBorder(                mxPaneId->getResourceURL(),                mxBorderCanvas,                aLocalBorderBox,                rUpdateBox,                msTitle);msTitle - can we not translate translate and/or generate that msTitle (SetTitle?) in the first instance ?Is that created from a template in:void PresenterController::UpdatePaneTitles (void)if so - we should fix it there in just one place :-)That template prolly comes from the (localised?) configuration and just needs changing there ?Anyhow - thanks again for looking at this - with a few tweaks (as above) I think we can make it a lot sweeter.Thanks !

Patch Set 1: Do not submitHeh - as rene says - the solver is not a solver - it is a legacy of our build system. All the final binaries that are built are moved into the solver, all the inter-module headers we compile against are located in the solver.The hope is that completing the gnumake work will kill the solver - and we can use the workdir/ instead - which has a friendlier name - and (hopefully) run the app directly out of that.Any chance you could re-work the README's and submit a new patch ? I just pushed a few cleanups for your previous commit that would be worth looking over.Thanks !

Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't submit thisHi Mathias,first thanks for your patch. It is great start; Well, it does some non-standard things. I suggest to re-shufle it a bit :-)1. You already mentioned that you were unsure about    downloading the files inside configure. I suggest to   do it using the download script.   You might already see the many @FILENAME@ entries in   ooo.lst.in. They are optional. If you do not define such    variable in configure, it will be empty in the generated    ooo.lst file and it will not be downloaded.2. If you use download, it will get the files into the   $TARFILE_LOCATION instead of $SRC_ROOT/moz/zipped.      I suggest to modify the related makefiles in "moz"    module to find the .zip archives in $TARFILE_LOCATION   Note that this approach follows the current trends.   In the past, we copied many 3rd party tarballs into   the related build subdirectories. We do not longer   do it. We already updated most makefiles to unpack the    tarballs directly from the $TARFILE_LOCATION.   3. I suggest to do not copy the dlls in configure because    it is not typical. Instead, I suggest to define variables   that will point to the files. Then you could copy the   files in the makefile that need to use the dlls.4. Please, do not remove the TABs from configure.in from    lines 4469-4515. These lines are copied into "Makefile"    that is later tested. TABs are important in Makefiles,   so your change breaks this test.Thanks a lot for working on it. Feel free to ask if you are in doubts.
